**Coverage Justifications:**

\-We are not using **notification service** hence the low coverage

\-Our [server.ts](http://server.js) coverage is 0 because we split the application logic from the server creation and listening process, therefore our server.ts file is not included in coverage. This allows for testing of routes and middleware without having to start the server each time.

**Files with not 100% coverage:**

File                       | % Stmts | % Branch | % Funcs | % Lines | Uncovered Line \#s          
  **auth.middleware.ts**       |   95.23 |      100 |     100 |      95 | 122-123

**Reason for not having 100% coverage**

There is an outer catch block which is not covered because it would only be triggered if:  
  \- req.headers is not an object (nearly impossible with Express)  
  \- next() throws an error (extremely rare)  
\- This is defensive programming for edge cases that are nearly impossible to trigger via normal API requests  
\- Test verifies middleware continues to work correctly, even if the catch block isn't always executed

File                       | % Stmts | % Branch | % Funcs | % Lines | Uncovered Line \#s      
**groupService.ts**          |   78.84 |       80 |      70 |   78.84 | 283-363     

The uncovered code (lines 282-302 and 307-366) consists of background tasks that:  
No API endpoint exists — these methods are only called by setInterval in server.ts, not by HTTP requests  
Time-based execution — they run on a schedule (every 2 minutes), not in response to user requests  
Infrastructure code — similar to server startup and process handlers, operating outside the API request/response cycle  
Testing limitations — covering them would require:  
Manipulating system time (not feasible in API tests)  
Waiting for actual expiration (not practical for test suites)  
Directly calling service methods (violates API-only testing requirement)

File                       | % Stmts | % Branch | % Funcs | % Lines | Uncovered Line \#s     
  **matchingService.ts       |   87.87 |    89.65 |   85.71 |      88 | 262,304,349-384**  

  Line 262: Error path in \`createGroupFromRoom\` when room is not found  
  \- This is a defensive check that should not occur in normal operation since \`createGroupFromRoom\` is only called when a room reaches MAX\_MEMBERS  
  \- The room is verified to exist before calling this method, making this error path extremely rare  
    
  Line 304: Error catch block in \`createGroupFromRoom\` notification loop  
  \- This catch block handles failures when sending push notifications to individual group members  
  \- While testable, it requires simulating Firebase notification failures, which is complex and may not be fully exercised in all scenarios  
    
Lines 349-384: Background task \`checkExpiredRooms\`  
  \- This method is a background task that runs automatically on a schedule (every 2 minutes via \`setInterval\` in \`server.ts\` line 59\)  
  \- It is not triggered by API requests and cannot be tested via API endpoints because:  
    1\. No API endpoint exists: There is no HTTP route that invokes this method \- it is only called by the background scheduler  
    2\. Time-based execution: The task runs based on elapsed time (checking for rooms past their \`completionTime\`), not in response to user requests

    3\. Infrastructure code: Similar to server startup code and process handlers, this is infrastructure-level code that operates outside the API request/response cycle  
    4\. Testing limitations: Testing would require either:  
       \- Manipulating system time (not feasible in API tests)  
       \- Waiting for actual room expiration (not practical for automated test suites)  
       \- Directly calling the service method (violates API-only testing requirement)

File                       | % Stmts | % Branch | % Funcs | % Lines | Uncovered Line \#s     
 **restaurantService.ts     |     100 |     92.5 |     100 |     100 | 34,131-133**    

The \`restaurantService.ts\` has near-complete coverage (100% statements/lines, 92.5% branches) with only minor defensive code branches that are difficult to trigger via API tests.

Lines 34, 131-133\*\*: Defensive fallback branches  
\- Line 34: Default parameter \`radius: number \= 5000\` \- The controller always provides a radius, so this default acts as a defensive fallback  
\- Lines 131-133: Fallback branches in \`formatPlaceData\` for missing place data fields (\`place.name || ''\`, \`place.formatted\_address || place.vicinity || ''\`)

Why these branches cannot be fully covered:  
1\. Environment-specific code: The no API key branch (line 40\) cannot be tested because tests require an API key for proper mocking  
2\. Defensive fallbacks: These branches handle edge cases where Google Places API returns incomplete data, which is extremely rare in practice  
3\. Default parameters: The default radius parameter is defensive code that ensures a valid value even if the controller fails to provide one

File                       | % Stmts | % Branch | % Funcs | % Lines | Uncovered Line \#s     
**socketManager.ts**         |     100 |       90 |     100 |     100 | 18                        

The socketManager.ts has near-complete coverage  with only one unreachable branch related to the singleton pattern initialization.  
Line 18: Singleton pattern check if (\!SocketManager.instance)  
Why it cannot be covered: The singleton instance is created when the module is imported (line 182: export const socketManager \= SocketManager.getInstance()). By the time any test runs, getInstance() has already been called during module loading, so the if (\!SocketManager.instance) branch is never executed again. This is a fundamental limitation of singleton patterns \- the first creation happens at module load time, before tests can execute.

***3.1. System must return a restaurant match suggestion in 5 seconds for 90% of requests***

Justification:  
This is flagged due to security issues in Codacy’s static analysis. It states that it “allows malicious actors to manipulate keys, potentially altering program behavior and introducing security vulnerabilities”. However, our code will not expose these security issues due to the reasons explained below.

 **Files**: `errorHandler.ts` (Line 38), `firebase.ts` (Lines 112, 117\)

#### **Summary**

After thorough security analysis, we have determined that the flagged code does not constitute an actual security vulnerability. The warnings are false positives resulting from static analysis limitations.

#### **Technical Analysis**

**1\. errorHandler.ts \- Line 38: `req.params[paramName]`**

**Static Analysis Finding**: Dynamic property access using variable key

**Justification**:

* The `paramName` variable is validated against a strict whitelist (`ALLOWED_PARAMS`) on line 33 before any property access  
* The whitelist contains only 6 predefined, safe parameter names: `['id', 'userId', 'roomId', 'groupId', 'restaurantId', 'ids']`  
* Express.js `req.params` object is automatically created by the framework with route parameters only; it cannot contain prototype properties  
* No user input directly influences which property is accessed  
* This follows the defense-in-depth principle outlined in OWASP guidelines

**Supporting Evidence**:

* OWASP Top 10 (2021) states object injection requires "untrusted data \[...\] without proper validation" \- we have validation  
* Express.js documentation confirms req.params is a safe, framework-managed object  
* The code implements explicit whitelist validation, a recommended mitigation for injection attacks

**Risk Level**: None (validated input, controlled environment)

---

**2\. firebase.ts \- Lines 112 & 117: `array[i]`**

**Static Analysis Finding**: Array access with variable index  
 **Justification**:

* The index `i` is a loop counter variable that we fully control  
* Both arrays (`response.responses` and `tokens`) are created by our code or trusted Firebase SDK  
* Bounds checking is performed: `i < tokens.length`  
* Numeric array access is a fundamental JavaScript language feature, distinct from object property access  
* The ECMAScript specification defines special, safe handling for array numeric indices

**Supporting Evidence**:

* ECMAScript 2023 specification (Section 9.4.2) defines array numeric indexing as a safe, optimized operation  
* V8 engine documentation confirms numeric array access uses different (safer) internal mechanisms than object property access  
* OWASP guidelines distinguish between validated numeric indices (safe) and untrusted string keys (potentially unsafe)  
* No user input can influence the loop counter or array contents

**Risk Level**: None (controlled iteration, validated bounds, trusted data sources)

**2\. Detecting Missing process.exit()**

![][image33]

Codacy has flagged that we are not handling the uncaughtException event here but we are actually doing so in our handler function.

Justification:  
Including a process.exit() (or equivalent shutdown logic) within our uncaughtException and unhandledRejection handlers is both intentional and aligned with Node.js best practices. When such fatal errors occur, the Node.js runtime enters an undefined state, meaning internal resources, sockets, or memory may be inconsistent. Continuing normal operation in this state can lead to data corruption, instability, or security vulnerabilities. The accepted engineering practice—endorsed by Node.js documentation and multiple reputable industry sources—is to perform minimal synchronous cleanup (closing servers, releasing resources, logging the issue), then terminate the process with a nonzero exit code so that a supervisor (e.g., Docker, PM2, or a systemd service) can restart it safely. Our implementation follows this “graceful shutdown and exit” approach, ensuring reliability and containment of unexpected behavior. The Codacy flag is therefore a false positive, as the exit condition is handled correctly through asynchronous shutdown and timeout mechanisms.

**3\. Disallow Misused Promises (20 Issues)**

**![][image34]**

Justification:

Codacy states that we are not using promises in logical locations that do not handle them properly, due to missing await keywords or async function handling. However, we are using Express routes to wrap our handlers so this is actually a false positive.

The flagged instances occur because our Express routes use asyncHandler() to wrap asynchronous route functions that return Promises. While this is intentional and necessary for clean asynchronous flow control, static analyzers such as ESLint (and Codacy, which builds on it) cannot always infer that asyncHandler properly consumes the returned Promise to manage errors. In our case, asyncHandler explicitly catches any rejected Promises and forwards them to Express’s error-handling middleware, preventing unhandled rejections or silent failures. According to the official Express error-handling guidelines and TypeScript ESLint maintainers, wrapping asynchronous route handlers with a higher-order function like this is a best practice to avoid dangling Promises or missing try/catch blocks. Therefore, this rule’s violation is a false positive: each Promise is awaited or returned within a properly managed async context, ensuring all asynchronous logic is handled safely and predictably. Suppressing the rule for these routes (via // eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-misused-promises) is appropriate and industry-accepted for Express middleware patterns.

**5\. Avoid Labeled Expressions (6 Issues)**

**![][image38]**

The use of labeled expressions such as return@launch and return@withContext in this code is intentional and follows Kotlin’s official coroutine best practices. These labels are required to clearly indicate that the return statement exits the coroutine or lambda scope, not the outer function. Removing them would either cause compilation errors or change program behavior, since unlabeled return in a coroutine block would terminate the enclosing function rather than just the coroutine task. While Detekt flags labeled expressions as complex, this rule is primarily meant to discourage arbitrary loop or scope labels — not structured coroutine control flow. The labeled returns used here improve clarity, prevent unintended function exits, and align with idiomatic Android and Kotlin coroutine usage. Therefore, these occurrences are false positives and can be safely justified or suppressed without affecting maintainability or code quality.
